Use `Microsoft.AspNetCore.WebUtilities.MultipartReader` to stream multipart sections directly to disk, bypassing model binding entirely.

**Key steps:**

1. **Disable form binding limits** and the default body size cap.
2. **Read the multipart body section-by-section**, copying each file section straight to a `FileStream`.

```csharp
// Program.cs
using Microsoft.AspNetCore.Http.Features;
using Microsoft.AspNetCore.WebUtilities;
using Microsoft.Net.Http.Headers;

var builder = WebApplication.CreateBuilder(args);

// Raise the max request body size (default is ~28 MB)
builder.WebHost.ConfigureKestrel(o => o.Limits.MaxRequestBodySize = 2L * 1024 * 1024 * 1024);

var app = builder.Build();

app.MapPost("/upload", async (HttpRequest request) =>
{
    if (!request.HasFormContentType ||
        !MediaTypeHeaderValue.TryParse(request.ContentType, out var mt) ||
        string.IsNullOrEmpty(mt.Boundary.Value))
    {
        return Results.BadRequest("Expected a multipart request.");
    }

    var boundary = HeaderUtilities.RemoveQuotes(mt.Boundary.Value).Value!;
    var reader = new MultipartReader(boundary, request.Body);

    MultipartSection? section;
    while ((section = await reader.ReadNextSectionAsync()) != null)
    {
        if (!ContentDispositionHeaderValue.TryParse(section.ContentDisposition, out var cd) ||
            !cd.IsFileDisposition())
        {
            continue; // skip non-file fields
        }

        var fileName = Path.GetRandomFileName(); // sanitize name
        var savePath = Path.Combine("/tmp/uploads", fileName);

        await using var stream = new FileStream(
            savePath, FileMode.Create, FileAccess.Write, FileShare.None,
            bufferSize: 81920, useAsync: true);

        await section.Body.CopyToAsync(stream);
    }

    return Results.Ok("Upload complete.");
})
.DisableAntiforgery();

app.Run();
```

**Why this works:**

| Concern | Solution |
|---------|----------|
| OOM from `IFormFile` | `MultipartReader` never materialises the whole file in memory—it streams chunk-by-chunk. |
| 28 MB default limit | `MaxRequestBodySize` is raised to 2 GB on Kestrel. |
| Disk I/O pressure | `FileStream` with `useAsync: true` + 80 KB buffer keeps memory flat. |

**Additional hardening (optional but recommended):**

```csharp
// Cap per-section read to prevent abuse
await section.Body.CopyToAsync(stream, cancellationToken);

// Or use a counting wrapper to enforce per-file limits:
const long maxFileSize = 2L * 1024 * 1024 * 1024;
long totalRead = 0;
var buffer = new byte[81920];
int bytesRead;
while ((bytesRead = await section.Body.ReadAsync(buffer)) > 0)
{
    totalRead += bytesRead;
    if (totalRead > maxFileSize)
        return Results.BadRequest("File too large.");
    await stream.WriteAsync(buffer.AsMemory(0, bytesRead));
}
```

**If you're behind IIS/HTTP.sys**, also set:

```csharp
// In web.config or via code for HTTP.sys:
builder.WebHost.UseHttpSys(o => o.MaxRequestBodySize = 2L * 1024 * 1024 * 1024);
```

The critical takeaway: **never bind large uploads to `IFormFile`**—read the raw multipart stream yourself and pipe it to disk.
